  "prompt": "In movies that play in the US, tires of cars are always squeaking. Why?",
  "response": "The squeaking tire sound in movies is largely an artistic sound effect added for dramatic emphasis, not necessarily reflecting real-world tire performance. It serves several purposes:\n\n1. Dramatic effect: Squealing tires create tension and excitement, especially during chase scenes or sudden maneuvers.\n\n2. Auditory cue: It helps the audience understand that a vehicle is making a sharp or sudden movement.\n\n3. Sound design tradition: It has become a cinematic convention that audiences expect and recognize.\n\nIn reality, modern tires on most road surfaces don't typically produce such dramatic squealing sounds unless:\n- The car is making an extremely sharp turn\n- Tires are worn or of low quality\n- The surface is very smooth and the car is moving at high speed\n- The driver is deliberately performing a maneuver like drifting\n\nMovie sound designers often exaggerate or artificially create these sounds to enhance the viewing experience, similar to how punches in movies sound much louder and more dramatic than in real life.",
